Q: In the coordinate plane, a triangle has vertices at (a,0), (b,0), and (x,y). If a>x>b>0>y, which of the following represents the area of that triangle?
Options: (a) (ay−by)/2 (b) (ab−ay)/2 (c) (by−ay)/2 (d) (ay+by)/x (e) (a−b)/2y
A:
The area of a triangle is given by the formula (base x height) / 2. In this case, the base is (x-a) and the height is y. So the area of the triangle is (x-a) x (y) / 2. The options are: (a) (ay-by)/2, (b) (ab-ay)/2, (c) (by-ay)/2, (d) (ay+by)/x, (e) (a-b)/2y. Since the base is (x-a) and the height is y, we have (x-a) x (y) / 2 = (a-b)/2y. So the answer is (e).

